    {
      "id": "1dbb1c4c_a38e89bc",
      "file_path": "feature-lifecycle/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/domain/models/nativ/rules/NativeDroolsPolicy.java",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": null,
      "message": "From junits:\n\n NativeDroolsPolicy domainDroolsPolicy = domainMaker.convertTo(<a-tosca-policy>, NativeDroolsPolicy.class);\n\nOne call and you have the data in your own domain specific set of classes that you can reuse downstream with all your pdp apps.  For example:  \n\ndomainDroolsPolicy.getProperties().getRulesArtifact().getVersion();\n\nThis is in contrast that just stole from models junit I wrote to navigate from tosca policy, need to deal with maps, having size of lists right, the name of fields, etc ..  The difference is obvious to me .. \n\n        Map<String, Object> props =\n                toscaVcpeSt.getToscaTopologyTemplate().getPolicies().get(0).get(OP_POLICY_NAME_VCPE).getProperties();\n        assertNotNull(props);\n\n        List<Object> operations = (List<Object>) props.get(\"operations\");\n        assertEquals(1, operations.size());\n        assertEquals(props.get(\"trigger\"), ((Map<String, Object>) operations.get(0)).get(\"id\"));\n\n        Map<String, Object> operation =\n                (Map<String, Object>) ((Map<String, Object>) operations.get(0)).get(\"operation\");\n        assertEquals(\"APPC\", operation.get(\"actor\"));\n        assertEquals(\"Restart\", operation.get(\"recipe\"));",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 477,
        "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
        "username": "jhh"
      },
      "updated": "2020-02-03 19:54:10.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "8f218b16_4941ebe5",
      "unresolved": true
    },
